Abu Zayd Sa'id ibn Aws al - Ansari ( Arabic : أبو زيد سعيد بن أوس الأنصاري‎ ; died 830 CE/215 AH ) was an Arab linguist and a reputable narrator of hadith .
Les Bowie ( November 10 , 1913 -- January 27 , 1979 ) was a Canadian - born special effects artist working mainly in Britain .
David McAlister ( 2 April 1951 -- 26 June 2015 ) was a British actor on television , in musicals , on stage and in film who was known for his voice - over work .
Sir Thomas William Meagher ( 26 March 1902 - -27 June 1979 ) was a medical practitioner who , starting in 1939 , served as Lord Mayor of Perth , Western Australia .
Vittorio Baldini ( died 21 February 1618 ) was an Italian printer and engraver .
John Thomas Job ( 21 May 1867 -- 4 November 1938 ) , was a Welsh minister , hymn - writer and poet .
Le Grand Henderson ( 1901 - -1964 ) , most often writing under the nom de plume `` Le Grand '' , was a writer and illustrator of books for all ages .
Henry Thring , 1st Baron Thring KCB ( 3 November 1818 -- 4 February 1907 ) , was a British lawyer and civil servant .
Július Jakoby ( born as Gyula Jakoby , Kassa , 28 March 1903 -- Košice , 15 April 1985 ) was a Hungarian painter living in Košice , a prominent figure of Hungarian and Slovak modernist art . His image is that of an loner , living on the fringe of society , struggling for survival at start .
Johann Andreas Kneucker ( 24 January 1862 -- 22 December 1946 ) was a German botanical collector who was a native of Wenkheim , a village that today is part of the community of Werbach , Baden - Württemberg .
William Wedge Darke ( 1810 - -1890 ) was an Australian colonist and surveyor , the son of John Darke of Hereford and Elizabeth Darke , née Wedge , and younger brother of John Charles Darke and a nephew of John Helder Wedge from whom he learnt his profession .
Ah Hoon ( died 1909 ) was a Chinese American comedian and associate of the On Leong Tong .
Louise Westergaard ( 1826 - -1880 ) , was a Danish reform pedagogue and pioneer on women 's education .
Musgrave Heighington ( ca.1680 -- 1764 ) was an English organist and composer .
Simple Kapadia ( 15 August 1958 -- 10 November 2009 ) was a Bollywood actress and costume designer .
Edmond Butler , 3rd/13th Baron Dunboyne ( 1595 - 1640 ) was an Anglo - Irish nobleman .
Walter Golaski ( 1913 in Torrington , Connecticut --1996 ) was an American Mechanical - Bio - Medical Engineer best known for developing Dense Knit Dacron Vascular Prostheses , which were the first practical artificial blood vessel replacements .
Annette Kirwan ( Sarah Annette Foster Kirwan ; died 6 April 1913 ) was the first wife of Edward Carson , Baron Carson .
Olaf Alfred Hoffstad ( 18 March 1865 -- 15 September 1943 ) was a Norwegian botanist , writer , school principal and Conservative politician .
Julia O'Connor ( 1890 - -1972 ) was an American labor leader and head of the National Telephone Operators ' Department of the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers ( IBEW ) .
Hugh Blair FRSE ( 7 April 1718 -- 27 December 1800 ) was a Scottish minister of religion , author and rhetorician , considered one of the first great theorists of written discourse .
Ali Bey Mihaloğlu or Gazı Alauddin Ali Bey Mihaloğlu , ( 1425 - -1507 ) was an Ottoman military commander in 15th century and the first sanjakbey of the Sanjak of Smederevo .
Kurt Starke ( 1911 in Berlin -- 19 January 2000 ) was a German radiochemist .
Sir Dinshaw Edulji Wacha ( 1844 - -1936 ) was a Parsi Indian politician from Bombay .
Anthony Hicks ( 26 June 1943 -- 26 May 2010 ) was a Welsh musicologist , music critic , editor , and writer .
Charles Nelson Tripp ( born Schenectady , New York , 1823 -- died New Orleans , 30 September 1866 ) was a pioneering geologist and bitumen businessman in Ontario .
Branca Eva de Gonta Syder Ribeiro Colaço ( July 8 , 1880 -- March 22 , 1945 ) , better known as Branca de Gonta Colaço , was a Portuguese writer , scholar and linguist .
Amalia Abad Casasempere ( Alcoy , 11 December 1897 -- Alcoy , 21 September 1936 ) was a Catholic woman killed during the Spanish Civil War .
Arthur Guinness ( 1725 -- 23 January 1803 ) was an Irish brewer and the founder of the Guinness brewery business and family .
Jan Visman ( 2 July 1914 , Deventer -- 19 February 2006 ) was a Dutch statistician who played a key role in building a bridge between sampling theory with its homogeneous populations and sampling practice with its heterogeneous sampling units and sample spaces .
Michele Foschini ( September 14 , 1711 - circa 1770 ) was an Italian painter , active in a late Baroque style .
Grigorios Konstantas ( Greek : Γρηγόριος Κωνσταντάς ; 1753 - -1844 ) was a Greek scholar and figure of the modern Greek Enlightenment .
Marie of Brienne ( c. 1225 - -1275 ) was the Empress consort of Baldwin II of Courtenay , Latin Emperor of Constantinople .
Tuoba Heru ( Chinese : 拓跋賀傉 ; pinyin : Tuòbá Hèrǔ ; died 325 ) ruled as prince of the Tuoba Dai 321 to 325 .
Eugen Lindner ( 11 December 1858 Leipzig - 12 November 1915 Weimar ) was a German composer , notably of opera .
Géo Voumard ( 2 December 1920 -- 3 September 2008 ) was a Swiss jazz pianist and composer .
General David Victor Belly de Bussy ( 19 March 1768 in Beaurieux -- 2 January 1848 in Beaurieux ) was a French officer during the Napoleonic Wars .
Susan Grace Benny , née Anderson , ( 1872 -- 5 November 1944 ) of Seacliff , South Australia was Australia 's first woman politician and the first Australian woman elected to local government .
Bernard Lacoste ( 22 June 1931 in Paris -- 21 March 2006 in Paris ) was a French fashion designer and businessman .
Richard Buzacott ( 7 September 1867 -- 10 January 1933 ) , Australian politician , was a Member of the Australian Senate from 1910 to 1923 .
Adrián Woll ( December 2 , 1795 -- February 1875 ) was a French Mexican general in the army of Mexico during the Texas Revolution and the military conflict between Mexico and the Republic of Texas which followed .
Dimitri Mitropoulos ( Greek : Δημήτρης Μητρόπουλος ) ( 1 March ( O.S. 18 February ) 1896 -- 2 November 1960 ) , was a Greek conductor , pianist , and composer .
Hermann Grote ( 7 July 1882 -- 12 August 1951 , Berlin ) was a German ornithologist known for his studies of African avifauna .
Henry Arthur ( 1801 - 9 June 1848 ) was nephew to the fourth Lieutenant - governor of Van Diemen 's Land , George Arthur .
Ralph Lainson OBE , FRS ( 21 February 1927 -- 5 May 2015 ) was a British parasitologist who studied leishmaniasis in Brazil .
Charles Macintosh FRS ( 29 December 1766 -- 25 July 1843 ) was a Scottish chemist and inventor of waterproof fabrics .
Sir Henry Morland ( 9 April 1837 -- 28 July 1891 ) was a British administrator in the Bombay Presidency of India who began his career in the navy .
Dimitrie Alexandresco ( variant spelling of last name : Alexandrescu ; 4 October 1850 in Iaşi -- 1925 ) was a Romanian encyclopedist .
William Sturm ( 1906 - -1981 ) was an animator , known for character development with Fleischer Animation Studios .
Sir Siegmund George Warburg ( 30 September 1902 -- 22 October 1982 ) was a German - born English banker .

Reverend Henry Cadwallader Adams ( 4 November 1817 -- 17 October 1899 ) was a 19th - century English cleric , schoolmaster and writer of children 's novels .

Mabel Mercer ( 3 February 1900 -- 20 April 1984 ) was an English - born cabaret singer who performed in the United States , Britain , and Europe with the greats in jazz and cabaret .

Turpilio ( died 409 ) was a Roman military commander , a Magister peditum .
Ena Baga ( 5 January 1906 -- 15 July 2004 ) was a British pianist and theatre organist .
Sir Roger Vaughan of Bredwardine ( died 25 October 1415 ) , also known as Roger Fychan the younger , was a Welsh gentleman , described as having possessed wealth , rank , and high respectability .
Ravinder Kapoor ( 15 December 1940 -- 3 March 2011 ) , popularly known as Goga Kapoor , was an Indian film actor , who appeared mostly in Bollywood films .
Karl Gustaf Torsten Sjögren ( /ˈʃoʊɡrən/ ; Swedish : ( ˈɧœˈɡrɪən ) ; 30 January 1896 -- 27 July 1974 ) was a Swedish psychiatrist and geneticist .
Abdullah Mohamed Omar ( 26 May 1934 -- 13 March 2004 ) , better known as Dullah Omar , was a South African anti - Apartheid activist , lawyer , and a minister in the South African cabinet from 1994 till his death .
Edward Geoffrey Toye ( 17 February 1889 -- 11 June 1942 ) , known as Geoffrey Toye , was an English conductor , composer and opera producer .
Aleksander Augezdecky ( or Aujezdecki ) ( born in the early sixteenth century , died in 1577 in Litomyšl ) was a Polish printer and publisher of Czech origin .
Audun Hugleiksson ( Hestakorn ) ( c. 1240 -- 2 December 1302 ) was a Norwegian nobleman at the end of the 13th century .
Jonathan Spilsbury ( 1737?--1812 ) was an English engraver , the brother of John Spilsbury , with whom he has sometimes been confused , and father of Maria Spilsbury .
Edward Larocque Tinker ( 1881 - 1968 ) was an American writer and philanthropist who developed a deep interest in the culture of Latin America and spent much of his life exploring it .
John Anthony Sydney Ritson DSO & Bar , OBE , MC ( 18 August 1887 -- 16 October 1957 ) was an English mines inspector and engineer who became professor of mining at Leeds University and at the Royal School of Mines , Imperial College , London .
Jack Stenhouse ( 20 November 1911 -- 31 October 1987 ) was an Australian rules footballer who played with Richmond , Essendon and Hawthorn in the Victorian Football League ( VFL ) .
Johann Samuel Heinsius ( 1686 - -1750 ) was a German bookseller and publisher based in Leipzig , best known for the works he published in collaboration with Johann Heinrich Zedler .
Martin Nadaud ( 17 November 1815 , Soubrebost , Creuse -- 28 December 1898 ) rose from being a peasant boy to becoming a revolutionary and Member of Parliament .
Edward Whitby ( died 8 April 1639 ) was an English lawyer and politician who sat in the House of Commons between 1614 and 1629 .
John Price Durbin ( 1800 - -1876 ) was a Methodist clergyman who served as Chaplain of the Senate and president of Dickinson College .
Henry Winder ( 15 May 1693 -- 9 August 1752 ) was an English nonconformist minister and chronologist .
Alan Redpath ( 9 January 1907 -- 16 March 1989 ) , was a well - known British evangelist , pastor and author .
Petrus Peckius the Elder ( born Pieter Peck , Zierikzee , 16 July 1529 ; died Mechelen , 16 July 1589 ) , also known as Pierre Peckius , was an eminent Netherlandish jurist , one of the first to write about international maritime law , and the father of Petrus Peckius the Younger .
Pan Chengdong ( Chinese : 潘承洞 ; Pinyin : Pān Chéngdòng ; 26 May 1934 -- 27 December 1997 ) was a Chinese mathematician made contributions in number theory , including the Goldbach 's conjecture .
John Lyon , 7th Lord Glamis ( c. 1521 - -1558 ) was a Scottish nobleman .
Thomas Bignall ( 8 January 1842 -- 19 September 1898 ) was an English cricketer who played first - class matches for Nottinghamshire between 1863 and 1878 as a right - handed batsman and very occasional fast bowler .
Émile Renouf ( 23 June 1845 -- 1894 ) was a French painter and draughtsman of the realism - impressionism school .
Abraham of the High Mountain ( died 406 ) was a teacher of Barsauma .
James Alan Hull ( 20 February 1945 -- 17 November 1995 ) was an English singer - songwriter and founding member of the Tyneside folk rock band Lindisfarne .
John Broadwood ( 6 October 1732 -- 17 July 1812 ) was the Scottish founder of the piano manufacturer Broadwood and Sons .
Michael Barrington ( 3 July 1924 -- 5 June 1988 ) was a British actor best known for his television work .
Indrani Aikath Gyaltsen ( 1952 - 1994 ) was an Indian novelist and columnist .
Hermann von Münster ( c. 1330 - March 1392 ) was a German master glassmaker , native of Münster , in Westphalia , and active in Lorraine .
Arthur Hugh Inkster ( c. 1866 -- 29 March 1907 ) was an Australian politician who represented the South Australian House of Assembly multi - member seat of Flinders from 1905 to 1907 , joining the Liberal and Democratic Union in 1906 .
Sophia Stacey ( 1791 - -1874 ) was a friend of the Romantic poet Percy Bysshe Shelley , to whom he dedicated the Ode which begins :
Mekled Hamied ( died December 2003 ) was a top Islamic Jihad commander who was killed during an Israeli air strike on his car in the last week of 2003 .
George Murnaghan ( 4 July 1847 -- 13 January 1929 ) was an Irish Nationalist Member of Parliament in the Parliament of the United Kingdom .
William H. Brand ( April 20 , 1824 Leonardsville , Madison County , New York -- 1891 ) was an American merchant and politician from New York .
William Robert Bousfield FRS ( 12 January 1854 -- 16 July 1943 ) was a British lawyer , Conservative politician and scientist .
Deane McMinn was a figure skating judge who was serving as team manager for the United States Figure Skating team attending the 1961 World Figure Skating Championships .
Sir Ralph Hare , 1st Baronet ( 24 March 1623 - 28 February 1672 ) was an English politician who sat in the House of Commons variously between 1654 and 1672 .
John Marshall , Lord Curriehill ( 1794 - -1868 ) was a Scottish judge .
Prince Francis Joseph of Braganza ( Portuguese : Príncipe Francisco José de Bragança ; 7 September 1879 -- 15 June 1919 ) was a member of the exiled branch of House of Braganza and an officer in the Austro - Hungarian Army .
Kirstine Fiil ( 23 August 1918 -- 25 August 1983 ) was a convicted member of the Danish resistance as part of the Hvidsten Group , whose husband , father and brother were executed by the German occupying power .
Geoffrey Malcolm Gathorne - Hardy , who wrote as G. M. Gathorne - Hardy ( 28 January 1878 - 7 January 1972 ) was an English soldier , writer and Norse specialist .
John Churchill Chase ( 1905 - -1986 ) was a cartoonist and writer .
John Hodgkiss ( ca.1820 -- 23 June 1897 ) was a politician in the early days of the Colony of South Australia
General Lord John Murray ( 14 April 1711 -- 26 May 1787 ) was a British general and politician .
Paul Scott Mowrer ( July 14 , 1887- April 7 , 1971 ) was an American newspaper correspondent , born in Bloomington , Illinois .
Bartholomew Traheron ( 1510?--1558 ? ) was an English Protestant writer and Marian exile .
David Schley Schaff ( 17 October 1852 , Mercersburg , Pennsylvania -- 2 March 1941 , Winter Park , Florida ) was a United States Presbyterian clergyman , educator and pioneer of American football .
William Rupert McCourt CMG ( 1884 -- 17 February 1947 ) was an Australian public servant who served as Clerk of the New South Wales Legislative Assembly .
Reuben Moulthrop ( 1763 - 1814 ) was an early American artist based in East Haven , Connecticut .
Thomas Bruce , 2nd Earl of Ailesbury and 3rd Earl of Elgin ( 1656 -- 16 December 1741 ) was the son of Robert Bruce , 2nd Earl of Elgin and Lady Diana Grey .
Edward William Cole , also known as ' E. W. Cole of the Book Arcade ' , ( 4 January 1832 -- 16 December 1918 ) was a bookseller and founder of the Book Arcade , Melbourne , Australia .
Povilas Višinskis ( 28 June 1875 , Ušnėnai , Kovno Governorate -- 23 April 1906 , Berlin ) was a Lithuanian writer , journalist , theatre director , and politician .
Pasang Lhamu Sherpa ( Nepali : पासाङ ल्हामु शेर्पा ; 10 December 1961 -- 22 April 1993 ) was the first Nepalese woman to climb the summit of Mount Everest .
Mohammad Jan Abdullah Wardak ( 1954 or 1955 -- 13 September 2008 ) was an Afghan politician and former Mujahideen commander .
Steven Groák ( 1944 - -1998 ) was head of research and development at Ove Arup Partnership in London , UK from 1990 - 1998 .
Crazy Lou ( died 1886 ) was the pseudonym of a New York showgirl and prostitute who was a well - known personality in the Bowery during the late 19th century .
John Micallef ( 1923 - -2003 ) was a Maltese minor philosopher .
Edward Holdsworth ( 1684 - -1746 ) was an English classical scholar , known as a neo - Latin poet .
Han Snel ( 1925 - -1998 ) was a famous Dutch painter born in Scheveningen , who moved to Indonesia in the 1940s to paint the island of Bali .
The Reverend Robinson Duckworth DD , CVO , VD , ( 4 December 1834 -- 20 September 1911 ) was present in the original boating expedition of 4 July 1862 during which Alice 's Adventures were first told by Lewis Carroll ( Charles Lutwidge Dodgson ) .
Charles Kingsley Adams CBE FBA ( 17 June 1899 -- 19 January 1971 ) was director , Keeper and Secretary of the National Portrait Gallery from 1951 to 1964 He was made CBE in 1954 and was a Fellow of the Society of Antiquaries .
Xiao Yu ( 574 - -647 ) , courtesy name Shiwen , posthumously known as Duke Zhenbian of Song , was an imperial prince of the Liang dynasty who later became an official under the Sui and Tang dynasties .
Kurt Kaiser ( 3 November 1906 -- 24 May 1970 ) , better known as Sydney John Kay , was a German - born composer , musician and theatre entrepreneur .
Sharof Rashidovich Rashidov ( in Cyrillic Uzbek : Шароф Рашидович Рашидов ; in Russian : Шараф Рашидович Рашидов Sharaf Rashidovich Rashidov ) ( 6 November ( O.S. 24 October ) 1917 -- 31 October 1983 ) was a Communist Party leader in the Uzbek Soviet Socialist Republic and a CPSU Central Committee Politbureau candidate member between 1961 and 1983 .
William Bankier ( 10 December 1870 -- 4 September 1949 ) billed as ' Apollo , the Scottish Hercules ' , was an early bodybuilder and strongman stage performer who in 1915 and 1919 was also ' King Rat ' of the showbusiness charity the Grand Order of Water Rats .
Panagiotis Pavlidis ( Greek : Παναγιώτης Παυλίδης ; died 1968 ) was a Greek shooter .
Éamon a Búrc ( 1866 - -1942 ) was a tailor and Irish storyteller or seanchaí .
Jan Mul ( 20 September 1911 - 30 December 1971 ) was a Dutch composer , mainly of church music .
Gerry O'Sullivan ( 1 April 1936 -- 5 August 1994 ) was an Irish Labour Party politician from Cork .
William Bouverie , 1st Earl of Radnor FRS ( 26 February 1725 -- 28 January 1776 ) was a British peer , styled Hon . William Bouverie from 1747 until 1761 .
Sir Edmund Frederick Du Cane ( 1830 - -1903 ) was an English major - general of the Royal Engineers and prison administrator .
Ludwig Haetzer ( also Ludwig Hetzer , Ludwig Hätzer and sometimes Ludwig Hatzer ) ( 1500 -- 4 February 1529 ) was an Anabaptist .
Edele Jernskjæg ( died 1512 ) was a Danish noble , courtier and the royal mistress of King John I of Denmark .
Sir Manasseh Meyer ( 1843 - -1930 ) was a British businessman and philanthropist who was a benefactor to the Jewish community in Singapore .
Sir John Dineley - Goodere , 5th Baronet ( 1729 - -1809 ) was an English eccentric .
Ivan Noble ( June 1967 -- 31 January 2005 ) was a British journalist who worked for BBC News Online and became well known for his diary documenting his fight against cancer .
Saint Carláen ( also called Cairlan , Carlan , Cairellán , Caurlan , Caerlan , Cáerlan , Cairlaene , Carillan , Cairlén , Ciarlaech , Cayrlan , Cairlani ) ( c. 530 -- 24 March 588 ) was the Bishop of Armagh , Ireland from 578 to 588 .
Antonina Makarova ( née Parfenova , Ginsburg by marriage , Russian : Антонина Макарова , 1921 -- 11 August 1979 ) was a Soviet war criminal and executioner who collaborated with the Nazis during World War II . From 1942 to 1943 she executed some 1,500 Soviet partisans and their family members by machine gun .
Arthur J. Frawley ( c. 1899 -- November 1969 ) was a Massachusetts politician who served as the 41st and 44th Mayors of Lynn , Massachusetts .
John Harington , 2nd Baron Harington ( 1328 - 1363 ) of Aldingham in Furness , Lancashire , was an English peer , who inherited the title Baron Harington in 1347 on the death of his grandfather John Harington , 1st Baron Harington ( 1281 - -1347 ) .
Jerzy Strzałka ( 28 March 1933 -- 13 October 1976 ) was a Polish fencer .
Colonel Sir John Luke Lowther KCVO CBE ( 17 November 1923 -- 11 April 2011 ) was a British soldier and Northamptonshire gentleman .
Jaime de Angulo ( 1887 - -1950 ) was a linguist , novelist , and ethnomusicologist in the western United States .
Lieutenant - Colonel Sir Thomas Wolseley Haig KCIE CSI CMG CBE ( 7 August 1865 -- 28 April 1938 ) was a civil servant in British India , then Professor at Trinity College , Dublin , and later a Scottish herald .
Cheomhae of Silla ( r. 247 - 261 , died 261 ) , often known by his title Cheomhae Isageum , was the twelfth ruler of the Korean kingdom of Silla .
Major Dr John Elsdale Molson TD ( 1863 - 1925 ) was a Canadian - born British Conservative politician and member of the Molson family of Montreal that started the famous Molson brewery .
Sir Charles Arundell ( died 9 December 1587 ) , was an English gentleman , lord of the manor of South Petherton , Somerset , notable as an early Roman Catholic recusant and later as a leader of the English exiles in France .
Johannes Lundson ( 12 October 1867 , Leppävirta -- 11 August 1939 , Salo ) was a Finnish politician from Young Finnish Party .
Sir William Langhorne , 1st Baronet ( c. 1631 -- 26 February 1715 ) was the Agent of Madras from January 1670 to 27 January 1678 .
Lawrence Daly ( 20 October 1924 -- 23 May 2009 ) was a coal miner , trade unionist and political activist .
Ivor Rees VC ( 18 October 1893 -- 11 March 1967 ) was a Welsh recipient of the Victoria Cross , the highest and most prestigious award for gallantry in the face of the enemy that can be awarded to members of the British and Commonwealth forces .
Sir Alfred Jodrell , 4th Baronet ( 1847 - 1929 ) was the fourth and last of the Jodrell Baronets , assuming the title in 1882 .
Mikhail Mikhaylovich Gerasimov ( Russian : Михаи́л Миха́йлович Гера́симов ) ( 2 September 1907 -- 21 July 1970 ) was a renowned Soviet archaeologist and anthropologist who developed the first technique of forensic sculpture based on findings of anthropology , archaeology , paleontology , and forensic science .
Ofusato ( 承察度 ) ( 1337 - -1398 ) was the first king of Nanzan , a kingdom in the southernmost end of Okinawa Island .
John Karl Hillers ( 1843 , Hanover , Germany -- 1925 ) was an American government photographer .
James Hemings ( 1765 -- 1801 ) was an American mixed - race slave owned and freed by Thomas Jefferson .
Frederick Samuel Wallis ( 22 November 1857 -- 13 November 1939 ) was a trade unionist and politician in the state of South Australia .
Albert Spaier ( 9 July 1883 -- 5 February 1934 ) was a French philosopher , professor of philosophy at the University of Caen .
James de Audley ( 1220 -- 1272 ) , or James de Aldithel and Alditheley , was an English baron .
Lawrence Carra ( 1909 - - March 30 , 2006 ) was an American professor of drama at Carnegie Mellon University in Pittsburgh , Pennsylvania , USA .
Medicine Arrows ( real name Rock Forehead or Stone Forehead ) ( c.1795 - -1876 ) was a Cheyenne chief and Keeper of the Medicine Arrows from 1850 until his death .
Pavao Ritter Vitezović ( Croatian pronunciation : ( pâʋao rîter ʋitěːzoʋitɕ ) ; 7 January 1652 -- 20 January 1713 ) was a noted Habsburg - Croatian writer , diplomat , and expansionist advocate .
Sir Fergus McMaster ( 3 May 1879 -- 8 August 1950 ) was an Australian businessman and aviation pioneer .
Sir John Jardine , 1st Baronet ( 27 September 1844 -- 26 April 1919 ) was Liberal MP for Roxburghshire from 1906 to 1918 .
Henry Hugh Clutton ( 12 July 1850 -- 9 November 1909 ) was an English surgeon who described painless symmetrical hydrarthrosis ( an accumulation of water in the cavity of a joint ) , especially of the knee joints : seen in hereditary syphilis .
Orlando Whistlecraft ( 11 November 1810 -- 3 March 1893 ) was an early English meteorologist who was born and died in the Eastern England village of Thwaite , Suffolk .
Joseph Vickers de Ville ( 1856 - -1925 ) was an English painter of landscapes and rural subjects .
Julius Katz ( March 9 , 1925 , New York , NY -- 1999 ) was United States Assistant Secretary of State for Economic and Business Affairs , appointed by President Ford .
Chi - Chien Wang ( Chinese : 王己千 ; pinyin : Wáng Jǐqiān ; Wade -- Giles : Wang Chi - chien ; 1907 -- July 3 , 2003 ) , better known as C. C. Wang , was a Chinese - born artist and art collector based in New York City .
John Cameron Peddie , ( 1887 -- 1968 ) known as `` J Cameron Peddie '' , was born on 16 May 1887 at Conland , Forgue , Aberdeenshire .
Jane Harriett Walker CH ( 24 October 1859 -- 7 November 1938 ) was an English medical doctor who first implemented the open - air method of treating tuberculosis in England .
Zayd ibn Harithah ( Arabic : زيد بن حارثة‎ ) or Zayd mawla Muhammad ( c. 581 -- 629 CE ) was a companion of Muhammad who was at one stage regarded as his ( adoptive ) son .
Westgarth Forster ( 1772 , Garrigill - 1835 , Garrigill ) was a geologist , mineralogist , and mining engineer .
Ernest Melville DuPorte ( 24 October 1891 - 31 July 1981 ) was a Canadian entomologist best known for his research in insect morphology .
Pasquale Ricca ( Civezza , 1854 - 1910 ) was an Italian painter , with an eclectic output of portraits , genre , still - life , seascape , and landscape subjects .
Liu Yizheng ( 柳詒徵 ) ( 1880 - -1956 ) was a Chinese modern historian , calligrapher , librarian , cultural scholar , educator and academic leader .
Ann George ( 5 March 1903 -- 8 September 1989 ) was a British actress best known for her role as Amy Turtle in the television soap opera Crossroads .
Lucebert ( /ˈluːtʃᵻbɛərt/ ; Lubertus Jacobus Swaanswijk ; 15 September 1924 -- 10 May 1994 ) was a Dutch artist who first became known as the poet of the COBRA movement .
Rajendra Krishan ( 6 June 1919 -- 23 September 1987 ) also credited as Rajinder Krishan , was an Indian poet , lyricist and screenwriter .
Reverend George Wilson Bridges ( 1788 - -1863 ) was a writer , photographer and Anglican cleric .
Martin Johann Schmidt , called Kremser Schmidt or Kremserschmidt , ( 25 September 1718 - 28 June 1801 ) , was one of the outstanding Austrian painters of the late Baroque / Rococo along with Franz Anton Maulbertsch .
Al - Malik al - Amjad Bahramshah was the Ayyubid emir of Baalbek between 1182 - 1230 ( 578 - 627 AH ) .
Laurie Gallagher ( 11 June 1924 -- 12 December 2012 ) was an Australian rules footballer who played with Collingwood in the Victorian Football League ( VFL ) .
Kūya ( 空也)(903 - 972 ) was an itinerant Japanese priest who , along with Genshin and Jakushin , was an early promoter of the practice of the nembutsu amongst the common people in order to attain salvation and entry into the Pure land of Amida .
Michel Honoré Bounieu ( 1740 - -1814 ) was a French painter of historical and genre subjects , and a mezzotint engraver .
Ray Harry ( 11 August 1909 -- 25 October 1991 ) was an Australian rules footballer who played with Carlton in the Victorian Football League ( VFL ) .
Arnoldus Clapmarius ( real surname Klapmeier , also known as Arnold Clapmar ) ( 1574 - -1604 ) was a German academic , jurist and humanist , known for his writings on statecraft .
Thorvald Meyer ( 23 September 1818 -- 3 February 1909 ) was a Norwegian businessman who built his fortune primarily on real estate development in Oslo , but also forestry .
Nana Asma'u ( full name : Nana Asma’u bint Shehu Usman dan Fodiyo , Arabic : نانا أسماء بنت عثمان فودي‎ ; 1793 - -1864 ) was a princess , poet , teacher , and daughter of the founder of the Sokoto Caliphate , Usman dan Fodio .
Tomislav Sertić ( 21 December 1902 -- 27 September 1945 ) was a member of the Croatian World War II Ustaše regime in charge of the Independent State of Croatia during World War II . He was born in Udbina on 21 December 1902 .
Luo Mu ( 1622 - -1706 ) was a painter , poet and prose writer born in Jiangxi .
Joseph Clinton Robertson ( c.1787 - -1852 ) , pseudonym Sholto Percy , was a Scottish patent agent , writer and periodical editor .
Art Brenner ( 1924 - 2013 ) was an American abstract sculptor and painter .
Fernande Caroen ( 27 July 1920 , Ostend -- 16 April 1998 , Ostend ) was a Belgian freestyle swimmer .
Patricia Preece ( January 1894 -- June 1966 ) , born Ruby Vivian Preece , was an English artist associated with the Bloomsbury Group and the second wife of painter Stanley Spencer , for whom she modelled .
Berthold of Reichenau ( died probably in 1088 ) was a Benedictine monk and chronicler of Reichenau Abbey .
Lanza del Vasto ( born Giuseppe Giovanni Luigi Maria Enrico Lanza di Trabia - Branciforte ; 29 September 1901 -- 5 January 1981 ) was a philosopher , poet , artist , catholic and nonviolent activist .
Narai ( Thai : นารายณ์ ; 1633 -- 11 July 1688 ) or Ramathibodi III ( รามาธิบดีที่ 3 ) or Ramathibodi Si Sanphet ( รามาธิบดีศรีสรรเพชญ ) was the king of Ayutthaya from 1656 to 1688 and arguably the most famous Ayutthayan king .
Giovanni Battista Montano ( 1534 - -1621 ) was an Italian architect , designer and engraver of primary importance as a recorder of Antique Roman architectural remains .
Canute Lavard ( Danish : Knud Lavard ) ( March 12 , 1096 -- 7 January 1131 ) was a Danish prince .
James Hamilton , 2nd Marquess of Hamilton and 4th Earl of Arran KG PC ( 1589 -- 2 March 1625 ) , styled Lord Aven from 1599 to 1604 , was a Scottish politician .
Phil Hunt ( 10 January 1884 - 9 June 1946 ) was a former Australian rules footballer who played with Melbourne in the Victorian Football League ( VFL ) .
Elizabeth Henry Campbell Russell ( 1749 - -1825 ) , a sister of Patrick Henry , was born in Hanover County , Virginia , to John Henry and Sarah Winston .
P. Chendur Pandian ( 1949 or 1950 -- 11 July 2015 ) was an Indian politician and incumbent Member of the Legislative Assembly of Tamil Nadu from Kadayanallur constituency .
Vera Scantlebury Brown OBE ( 7 August 1889 -- 14 July 1946 ) was an Australian medical practitioner and pediatrician in Victoria , Australia .
Ephraim London died in New York City on 12 June 1990 from complications from diabetes .
Jennifer F. M. Horne ( died 5 October 2008 in Nanyuki , Kenya ) also known as Jenny Horne or after her marriage as Jennifer Horne - Short was a Kenyan ornithologist and bioacoustican .
Gerard Thomas ( 1663 - -1721 ) was a late Flemish Baroque painter who specialized in studio and picture gallery interiors .
Jijeung of Silla ( 437 - -514 ) ( r.500 - 514 ) was the 22nd ruler of the Korean kingdom of Silla .
Ann Howe ( c.1802 - -1842 ) was a newspaper proprietor in the colony of New South Wales who published a paper which vigorously supported the liberal Governor Richard Bourke and represented the emancipist ( ex - convict ) voice .
Kalman J. Cohen ( c. 1932 -- 12 September 2010 ) was an American economist and among the pioneers of studying market microstructure .
Maelgwn ap Rhys ( c. 1170 - -1230 ) was prince of part of the kingdom of Deheubarth in south west Wales .
John A. Daniel ( c.1931 - 2011 ) ( aka John Daniels ) was magician and a collector and dealer of magician memorabilia , Baranger Motion machines , vintage electric trains , toys , antique carousels and other collectibles .
Maria Perosino ( 10 December 1961 -- 16 June 2014 ) was an Italian author and art historian .
Guillaume de Morlaye ( c. 1510-c . 1558 ) was a French Renaissance era lutenist , composer and music publisher .
Little Turkey ( 1758 - -1801 ) was First Beloved Man of the Cherokee people , becoming , in 1794 , the first Principal Chief of the original Cherokee Nation .
Marguerite Joly ( 1637 - 19 December 1681 ) was a professional French poisoner .
Rhoda Bulter ( 15 July 1929 -- 1994 ) , Shetland author , is one of the best - known Shetland poets of recent times .
Fu Deng ( Chinese : 苻登 ; 343 - -394 ) was an emperor of the Chinese / Di state Former Qin .
Tor Hagfors ( 18 December 1930 -- 17 January 2007 ) was a Norwegian scientist , radio astronomer , radar expert and a pioneer in the studies of the interactions between electromagnetic waves and plasma .
Dharmasthala Ratnavarma Heggade was an Indian philanthropist , educationist and legislator who is best known for being the hereditary administrator(Dharmadhikari ) of the Dharmasthala Manjunatha Temple from 1955 to 1968 .
Andrew Blain Baird died in Rothesay , Isle of Bute Scotland on 9 September 1951 .
Pierre Julien ( 20 June 1731 -- 17 December 1804 ) was a French sculptor who worked in a full range of rococo and neoclassical styles .
Basil Montagu ( 24 April 1770 -- 27 November 1851 ) was a British jurist , barrister , writer and philanthropist .
Karl Pohlig ( 10 February 1864 -- 17 June 1928 ) was a German Bohemian conductor born in Teplitz , Bohemia , Austrian Empire .
Francis Lucy ( born ca . 1600 -- 1687 ) was an English lawyer and politician who sat in the House of Commons from 1624 to 1629 .
Eduard Raimund Baierlein ( 29 April 1819 , Posen -- 12 October 1901 ) was a German Lutheran missionary .
Hugh C. Robertson , ( 1845 - -1908 ) , was an American studio potter who is the first recognized potter to have worked with nonrepresentational ceramic decoration glazes .
Chandrakant Sardeshmukh ( died 15 August 2011 ) was a Hindustani classical sitar player of the Maihar Gharana ( school ) .
José Dapena Laguna , ( 28 July 1912 - 20 September 1991 ) was a Puerto Rican politician and Mayor of Ponce , Puerto Rico in 1956 .
Maria Magdalena Mathsdotter ( 21 March 1835 -- 31 March 1873 ) was a Swedish Sami who in 1864 took the initiative to the foundation of schools for Sami children in Lapland .
Janet Horne ( died 1727 ) was an alleged witch from Scotland , and the last person to be executed for witchcraft in the British Isles .
Archibald Campbell , 9th Earl of Argyll ( 26 February 1629 -- 30 June 1685 ) was a Scottish peer .
John Buddle ( 15 September 1773 -- 10 October 1843 ) was a prominent self - made mining engineer and entrepreneur in North East England .
Æthelmær the Stout or Æthelmær Cild ( died 1015 ) was ealdorman of the western provinces ( or south - western England ) from c. 1005 to 1015 .
Baron Frederick Joseph Eugene de Kleist ( January 18 , 1853 -- 1911 ) , was a pioneering German organ builder , who in founding the North Tonawanda Barrel Organ Factory , started the American style of Band organs .
Josep Cusachs i Cusachs ( 1851 , Montpellier - 1908 , Barcelona ) was a Catalonian soldier and painter .
Sir Peter Probie ( died March 1625 ) was an English politician who sat in the House of Commons at times between 1593 and 1598 .
Carl Gotthard Langhans ( 15 December 1732 -- 1 October 1808 ) was a Prussian builder and architect .
James Arbuckle ( 1700 -- 1742 ? ) was an Irish poet and critic , associated politically with Presbyterianism and Whiggism .
Orpha - F. Deveaux ( July 24 , 1872 -- December 1933 ) was an American organist , pianist , and music educator .
Rudolph I , Count Palatine of Tübingen ( 1160 -- 17 March 1219 ) was the eldest son of Count Palatine Hugo II of Tübingen .
Allen Turner ( 24 October 1891 -- 7 January 1961 ) was an English cricketer who played first - class cricket for Derbyshire in 1920 .
Nshan Beshiktashlian ( Armenian : Նշան Պէշիկթաշլեան , born in Istanbul , Ottoman Empire , 1898 - died Paris , France , 1972 ) was an Armenian poet , writer , satirist , and novelist .
Virna Pieralisi ( Italian pronunciation : ( ˈvirna pjeraˈliːzi ) ; 8 November 1936 -- 18 December 2014 ) , better known as Virna Lisi ( Italian pronunciation : ( ˈvirna ˈliːzi ) ) , was an Italian actress .
Samo founded the first recorded political union of Slavic tribes , known as Samo 's Empire ( realm , kingdom , or tribal union ) , stretching from Silesia to present - day Slovenia , ruling from 623 until his death in 658 .
Ernst Mayer ( 24 June 1796 -- 21 January 1844 ) was a German sculptor in the classical style .
Dashrath Manjhi ( c. 1934 -- 17 August 2007 ) , also known as `` Mountain Man '' , was a poor labourer in Gehlaur village , near Gaya in Bihar , India , who carved a path 360 ft long , 30 ft wide and 25 ft high through a hillock using only a hammer and chisel .
Oliver Eaton Cromwell Jr. ( 1892 - -1987 ) was an American mountain climber who made many first ascents in the Canadian Rockies and was a member of the 1939 K2 expedition .
William Suhr ( born March 31 , 1896 Kreutzberg - 2003 ) was an American art conservator , and conservator of the Frick Collection , from 1935 to 1977 .
John George Dodson , 1st Baron Monk Bretton PC ( 18 October 1825 -- 25 May 1897 ) , known before 1884 as John George Dodson , was a British Liberal politician .
Leonor de La Guerra y Vega Ramírez ( died 1816 ) was a heroine of the Venezuelan War of Independence .
Washington Shirley , 8th Earl Ferrers ( 13 November 1760 -- 2 October 1842 ) , styled Hon . Washington Shirley from 1778 to 1827 , was a British nobleman .
James Buckley Stringer Davis , generally known as Stringer Davis ( 4 June 1899 -- 29 August 1973 ) , was an English character actor on the stage and in films and a British army officer who served in both World Wars .
Catherine Helen Spence ( 31 October 1825 -- 3 April 1910 ) was a Scottish - born Australian author , teacher , journalist , politician , leading suffragist , and Georgist .
Roy Suarez Garcia ( 1945 - -2003 ) AKA `` Chicano Roy '' was an American motorcycle builder and inventor .
Iain McColl ( 27 January 1954 -- 4 July 2013 ) was a Scottish film and television actor , best known for his roles on British television series .
Erik Harry Stenqvist ( 25 December 1893 -- 9 December 1968 ) was a Swedish road racing cyclist .
John Trilleck ( died 20 November 1360 ) was a medieval Bishop of Hereford .
Simon Brome , Brown or Browne ( died 1603 ) , of St. Andrew 's , Canterbury , Kent , was an English politician .
Yang Yin ( 楊愔 ) ( 511 - -560 ) , courtesy name Zhunyan ( 遵彦 ) , nickname Qinwang ( 秦王 ) , was a high - level official of the Chinese dynasty Northern Qi .
Peter dalle Carceri ( Italian : Pietro dalle Carceri , died 1340 ) was a Triarch of Euboea and Baron of Arcadia .
Una Padel OBE ( 21 July 1956 -- 29 August 2006 ) was a British criminal - justice reformer , known for her work in penal reform .
Salomon Mesdach ( c.1600 -- 1632 ) , was a Dutch Golden Age painter .
Per Larssen ( 11 June 1881 -- 21 October 1947 ) was Norwegian Minister of Trade 1931 - 1932 in Kolstad 's Cabinet .
Yunus Khan ( c. 1416 - -1487 ) ( Uyghur : يونس خان‎ ) , was Khan of Moghulistan from 1462 until his death .
Wen Jiao ( 溫嶠 ) ( 288 - -329 ) , courtesy name Taizhen ( 太真 ) , formally Duke Zhongwu of Shi'an ( 始安忠武公 ) , was a renowned Jin Dynasty ( 265 - 420 ) general and governor .
Helmut Vetter ( 21 March 1910 - 2 February 1949 ) was an SS - Hauptsturmführer and a Nazi war criminal .
Victor Bernau ( 14 January 1890 -- 13 May 1939 ) was a Norwegian singer , actor and theatre director .
Strachkvas ( Kristián ) ( September 28 , 929 or 935 , Prague - 996 , Prague ) was a prince of Bohemia , son of Boleslav I and brother of Boleslav II , all members of the Přemyslid dynasty .
Sir Thomas Percival Creed KBE MC KC ( 29 January 1897 -- 11 May 1969 ) was a lawyer and educationist .
Fu Yi ( Chinese : 傅奕 ; pinyin : Fù Yì ; Wade -- Giles : Fu I ; 554−639 ) was a Sui dynasty official who later became historiographer during the reign of Emperor Gaozu of the Tang dynasty .
Friedrich Wilms ( 19 April 1848 Münster , Westphalia - 2 March 1919 Berlin - Steglitz ) , was a German apothecary , botanical collector and traveller .
Jostein Nyhamar ( 23 September 1922 -- 30 July 1993 ) was a Norwegian magazine editor , biographer and politician for the Labour Party .
Alfred Dubucand ( 25 November 1828 -- 1894 ) was a French animalier sculptor of the 19th century .
Declan Flynn was an Irish gay man attacked and killed in Fairview Park in Dublin on 9 September 1982 .
Joseph Cundall ( 22 September 1818 Norwich -- 10 January 1895 Wallington , London ) , was a Victorian English writer under the pseudonym of `` Stephen Percy '' , a pioneer photographer and London publisher of children 's books .
Robert Seymour Conway ( 1864 -- 1933 ) was a British classical scholar and comparative philologist .
Claude Lorrain ( French : ( klod lɔ.ʁɛ̃ ) ; born Claude Gellée ( ʒəle ) , dit le Lorrain ; traditionally just Claude in English ; c. 1600 -- 23 November 1682 ) was a French painter , draughtsman and engraver of the Baroque era .
Jemima Yorke , 2nd Marchioness Grey and Countess of Hardwicke ( 9 October 1723 -- 10 January 1797 ) was a British peeress .
Menzies Dickson ( ca . 1840 -- 1891 ) was a photographer in Hawaii .
Wiktor Budzyński ( Lithuanian : Viktoras Budzinskis ) , born March 7 , 1888 in the village of Eustachow near Vilkaviškis , died 1976 in Puszczykowo near Poznań , was an ethnic Polish politician , active in the interbellum period in the Republic of Lithuania .
Augustus Daniel Imms FRS ( 14 August 1880 , Moseley , Worcestershire -- 3 April 1949 Tipton St. John near Sidmouth , Devon ) was an English educator , research institution administrator and entomologist .
Ida Königsmarck ( died 1450 ) , was a Swedish noble and fief - holder , known for her legendary defense of Kastelholm Castle on Åland in Swedish Finland during the Engelbrekt rebellion in 1433 .
Edward Vason Jones ( August 3 , 1909 -- October 1 , 1980 ) , a neoclassical architect and member of the Georgia School of Classicism , began his career in 1936 with the design and construction of the Gillionville Plantation near his hometown of Albany , Georgia .
Saints Rufus and Zosimus ( died 107 AD ) are 2nd century Christian martyrs venerated by the Roman Catholic and the Eastern Orthodox churches .
Karoline Bjørnson ( née Reimers , 1 December 1835 -- 27 June 1934 ) was a Norwegian actress .
Franz Joseph II , Prince of Liechtenstein ( Franz Josef Maria Aloys Alfred Karl Johannes Heinrich Michael Georg Ignaz Benediktus Gerhardus Majella ; 16 August 1906 -- 13 November 1989 ) was the Sovereign Prince of Liechtenstein from 1938 until his death .
Louis Masreliez ( 1748 -- 19 March 1810 ) , born Adrien Louis Masreliez , was a Swedish painter and interior designer .
Ralph de Monthermer , 1st Baron Monthermer , Earl of Gloucester , Hertford and Atholl ( c. 1270 - 5 April 1325 ) was an English nobleman .
Venerable Francesco Antonio Marcucci ( 27 November 1717 -- 12 July 1798 ) was a Roman Catholic Italian bishop and a member of the Secular Franciscan Order .
Major General Sir Jeremiah Bryant CB ( 1783 - 10 June 1845 ) was a British Army officer in the Bengal Army .
Giuseppe Lucatelli ( 1751 - 1828 ) was an Italian painter and architect , active in a Neoclassical style .
Orazio Farinati ( 1559 - -1616 ) was a late Mannerist Italian painter .
Carlos Wiesse Portocarrero ( 1859 - -1945 ) was a Peruvian scholar and historian .
Sir George Mellish ( 19 December 1814 -- 15 June 1877 ) was an English barrister , judge of the Court of Appeal in Chancery , and member of the Judicial Committee of the Privy Council .
Werner Zerweck ( 14 March 1899 in Munich -- 10 September 1965 ) was a German chemist , inventor and industrial leader , who served as CEO of the chemical and pharmaceutical company Cassella from 1953 to 1963 .
George Skene ( 9 May 1749 -- 27 April 1825 ) , of Skene , was a Scottish soldier and politician .
Lalit Chandra Nath ( Assamese : ললিত চন্দ্ৰ নাথ ) popularly known as Lalit Oja or Lalit Chandra Nath Oja ( 1923 - 21 October 2013 ) was a notable person from Assam .
Maria Anna Fesemayr ( sometimes spelled Fesemayer ) ( 1743 - -1782 ) was a Salzburg court singer , who sang in Mozart 's Die Schuldigkeit des ersten Gebots and created the role of Ninetta in his La finta semplice .
James Sadleir ( c. 1815 -- 4 June 1881 ) was a member ( MP ) of the British House of Commons , chiefly notable for being one of the few members expelled by that body .
Ștefan Răzvan ( died December 1595 ) was a Voivode ( Prince ) of Moldavia ( between 24 April 1595 and August 1595 ) of Romani descent from the historical Romanian state of Wallachia .
Jan Gruter or Gruytère , Latinized as Janus Gruterus ( 3 December 1560 -- 20 September 1627 ) , was a Flemish - born philologist , scholar , and librarian .
Jovan Šević or Ivan Šević ( Serbian : Јован Шевић , Russian : Иван Егорович Шевич ; died c. 1764 ) was an 18th - century military officer of Serb origin .
René Thirifays ( 8 October 1920 - -17 October 1986 ) was a Belgian football player who finished top scorer of the Belgian League with 26 goals in 1949 while playing for Sporting Charleroi .
Kusumavati Deshpande ( Devanagari : कुसुमावती देशपांडे ) ( 1904 - -1961 ) was a Marathi writer from Maharashtra , India .
Diarmuid Mac Bruideadha ( Brody ) , Irish poet , died 1563 .
Raymond Kirsch ( 18 January 1942 - 11 March 2013 ) was a Luxembourgian businessman , economist , and administrator .
Sir Edward Hoare , 2nd Baronet ( 14 March 1745 - 30 April 1814 ) was an Anglo - Irish politician .
Johan Nicolay Tønnessen ( 30 November 1901 -- 27 December 1987 ) was a Norwegian historian and schoolteacher .
Edgar Rickard ( 1874 - -1951 ) was a mining engineer and lifelong confidant of U.S. President Herbert Hoover .
Francesco De Masi ( 11 January 1930 -- 6 November 2005 ) was an Italian conductor and film score composer .
Johann Walter , also known as Johann Walther or Johannes Walter ( original name : Johann Blankenmüller ) ( 1496 -- 25 March 1570 ) was a Lutheran composer and poet during the Reformation period .
Maurice Webster ( 12 November 1899 -- February 1978 ) was an English international footballer , who played as a centre half .
Thomas Prichard Rossiter ( 1818 -- 1871 ) was a 19th - century American artist known for his portraits and paintings of historical scenes .
Aasa Helgesen born Aasa Røinesdal ( 11 February 1877 -- 29 April 1968 ) was a Norwegian midwife and politician .
Lucio Quarantotto ( 1957 -- 31 July 2012 ) was an Italian songwriter best known for writing the lyrics for `` Con te partirò '' ( `` With you , I will leave '' ) , to music composed by Francesco Sartori for Andrea Bocelli .
Will Stuckey ( 27 July 1873 -- 21 September 1928 ) was an Australian rules footballer in the Victorian Football League .
Warren Widener ( 1938 - 2013 ) was a former Mayor of Berkeley , California , and former member of the Alameda County Board of Supervisors .
( Alfred ) Melville Cook ( 18 June 1912 -- 22 May 1993 ) was a British organist , conductor , composer and teacher .
Jean Bouillon ( 20 December 1926 Uccle , Belgium - 31 March 2009 ) was a Belgian marine biologist and expert on Hydrozoa .
Michele Ridolfi ( Lucca 1795 -- Lucca , November 1 , 1854 ) was an Italian painter and art critic .
Marguerite Macé - Montrouge ( born Victoire Macé on 24 March 1836 , died 26 November 1898 in Paris ) , became a professional actress at the age of 14 , and was an early member of Offenbach 's troupe , before enjoying a long stage career in Paris and elsewhere .
Nathaniel Ryder , 1st Baron Harrowby ( 3 July 1735 -- 20 June 1803 ) was a British peer and Member of Parliament .
Jackie Leven ( 18 June 1950 -- 14 November 2011 ) was a Scottish songwriter and folk musician .
Samuel Mullen ( 27 November 1828 -- 29 May 1890 ) was an Irish - born bookseller , active in Australia .
Ludwig Lorenz von Liburnau ( 26 August 1856 , Fiume - 9 December 1943 , St. Gilgen ) was an Austrian zoologist .
Nevdür Hanımefendi ( c. 1861 - c. 1927 , birth name Şadiye Nakaşvili , other names Nevdürr , Nev - Dürr , Noder ) was the wife of Sultan Murad V of the Ottoman Empire .
Waruhiu Itote ( 1922 -- 30 April 1993 ) also known as General China , was one of the key leaders of the Mau Mau rebellion alongside Dedan Kimathi , Stanley Mathenge and Musa Mwariama .
Lord Robert William Brian McConnell , Baron McConnell ( 25 November 1922 -- 25 October 2000 ) was an Ulster Unionist MP in the Northern Ireland House of Commons .
Christian Ignatius Borissow ( 4 April 1788 - 2 November 1867 ) was an expert on commerce and a teacher of languages with Finnish roots who immigrated to Great Britain before 1819 .
Sir Frederick Arthur Whitaker KCB , DEng ( 17 July 1893 -- 13 June 1968 ) was a British civil engineer .
Vojislav Korać ( 1924 - -2010 ) was a Yugoslav and Serbian historian on architecture , academic and professor .
Hermine Freed ( May 29 , 1940 New York City -- November 21 , 1998 New York City ) was an American painter and video artist .
Frans Molenaar ( Dutch pronunciation : ( frɑns ˈmoːləˌnaːr ) ; 11 May 1940 -- 9 January 2015 ) was a Dutch fashion designer .
Empress Dowager Ding ( 丁太后 , personal name unknown ) ( died 402 ) , formally Empress Xianyou ( 獻幽皇后 , literally `` the wise and lonely empress '' ) was an empress dowager of the Chinese / Xianbei state Later Yan .
Robert Mallet , FRS , MRIA ( 3 June 1810 -- 5 November 1881 ) , Irish geophysicist , civil engineer , and inventor who distinguished himself in research on earthquakes and is sometimes called the father of seismology .
Isaac Newton Phelps ( 1802 - -1888 ) was a New York dry goods merchant who , after retiring in 1853 , took up a second career in banking , brokerage and property .
Wilhelm von Kobell ( 6 April 1766 -- 15 July 1853 ) was a German artist , a painter , printmaker and teacher .
John Alan Coey ( 12 November 1950 -- 19 July 1975 ) was an American soldier who served in the Rhodesian Army as one of `` the Crippled Eagles '' , a loosely organised group of US expatriates fighting for the unrecognised government of Rhodesia ( today Zimbabwe ) during that country 's Bush War .
Saint Vicelinus ( also Vicelin , German : Vizelin ; 1086 -- December 12 , 1154 ) was a German bishop of Oldenburg in Holstein who was considered the apostle of Holstein .
José Yacopi ( Victoria , Spain , 28 December 1916 - -San Fernando , Argentina , 11 August 2006 ) was a Spanish , and later Argentinian luthier .
Wout Buitenweg ( 24 December 1893 -- 10 November 1976 ) was a Dutch football player scored 14 goals in 11 games for the Dutch national side .
Sir Francis Foljambe , 1st Baronet ( died 1640 ) was Member of Parliament for Pontefract in 1626 and High Sheriff of Derbyshire in 1633 .
Emilio Fagot ( 2 February 1883 - 28 January 1946 ) was a Puerto Rican politician and Mayor of Ponce , Puerto Rico from 1929 to 1933 .
Johann Heinrich Gossler ( born 28 March 1775 , died 3 April 1842 ) was a Hamburg banker and grand burgher , a member of the Berenberg - Gossler - Seyler banking dynasty , a co - owner ( from 1798 ) of the Berenberg Bank and a senator of Hamburg from 1821 .
Setske de Haan ( 24 November 1889 -- 31 October 1948 ) , better known by her pen name Cissy van Marxveldt , was a Dutch writer of children 's books .
Cvjetko Popović ( 1896 -- 9 June 1980 ) was a Bosnian Serb who was involved in the 1914 assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria .
James William Wallack ( c. 1794 - -1864 ) was an Anglo - American actor and manager , born in London , and brother of Henry John Wallack .
Daniel Kabiljo ( 6 March 1894 , Sarajevo -- 1944 , Jasenovac concentration camp ) was a Yugoslav Jews Sephardi artist .
Air Chief Commandant Dame Katherine Jane Trefusis Forbes , Lady Watson - Watt , DBE ( 21 March 1899 -- 18 June 1971 ) , known as Jane Trefusis Forbes , was a businesswoman and the first director of the Women 's Auxiliary Air Force ( 1939 - -43 ) .
Benoni Danks ( ca 1716 -- 1776 ) was a New England Ranger and political figure in Nova Scotia , and representative of Cumberland County in the Nova Scotia House of Assembly from 1765 to 1770 .
Carl Rønneberg ( 10 August 1779 -- 29 January 1858 ) was a Norwegian merchant , ship owner and fish exporter .
Colonel Philip Pieterse Schuyler ( 1628 - 1683 ) was born in Amsterdam , Holland in the Republic of the Seven United Provinces , in 1628 as the son of Pieter Tjercks and Geertruyt Philips Van Schuylder .
Anthony Barnewall ( 1721 - -1739 ) , was an officer in the Austrian army .
Jack Bridger Chalker ( 10 October 1918 -- 15 November 2014 ) , was a British artist and teacher best known for his work recording the lives of the prisoners of war building the Burma Railway during World War Two .
Karl Gottlieb Guichard ( 1724 - -1775 ) also known as Quintus Icilius , was a soldier and military writer .
Thomas Gee ( 24 January 1815 - 28 September 1898 ) , was a Welsh Nonconformist preacher , journalist and publisher .
Friedrich August Rudolph Kolenati ( 12 September 1812 -- 17 July 1864 ) was a Czech - German botanist and zoologist active primarily in Prague and Brno .
Harold Douglas Ursell ( 1907 - -1969 ) was an English mathematician who is best known for Ursell function .
Mary Rae Knowling ( 21 October 1923 --31 January 2013 ) was a South African medical doctor , Anglican and philanthropist .
Rear - Admiral Charles Steevens ( ca . 1705 - 20 May 1761 ) was a Royal Navy officer who became Commander - in - Chief of the East Indies Station .
Swaroop Kishen Reu ( 13 July 1930 -- 21 November 1992 ) was an Indian Test cricket umpire .
Theodosius Forrest ( 1728 -- 1784 ) was an English author , balladeer , playwright and lawyer .
Jean Negulesco ( born Ioan Negulescu ; 29 February 1900 ( O. S. ) -- 18 July 1993 ) was a Romanian - American film director and screenwriter .
Richard Bowyer Smith ( 2 September 1837 in London , England -- 4 February 1919 in Subiaco , Western Australia ) was an Australian inventor .
Thomas Gleadowe - Newcomen , 2nd Viscount Newcomen ( 18 September 1776 -- 15 January 1825 ) , known as The Honourable Sir Thomas Gleadowe - Newcomen , Bt , between 1807 and 1817 , was an Irish politician .
Adalbert Zuckschwerdt ( 1 January 1874 -- 1 July 1945 ) was captain ( Korvettenkapitän ) of the German raider SMS Cormoran , which sailed from the German colony of Tsingtao ( Qingdao today ) , China , until she finally docked was and interned at Guam by the Americans .
Vaithamanithi Mudumbai Kothainayaki Ammal ( 1 December 1901 -- 20 February 1960 ) was a Tamil writer , novelist and journalist who is remembered as the first woman to occupy the editorial board of a Tamil magazine .
Sydney Thompson Dobell ( 5 April 1824 -- 22 August 1874 ) was an English poet and critic , and a member of the so - called Spasmodic school .
Barbarina Brand , Lady Dacre ( née Ogle ; 1768 - -1854 ) , was an English poet , playwright , and translator .
Sir Muthu Coomaraswamy ( Tamil : முத்து குமாரசுவாமி ; 23 January 1834 -- 4 May 1879 ) was a Ceylon Tamil lawyer , writer and member of the Legislative Council of Ceylon .
Gunnar Emil Garfors ( 1900 - 1979 ) was a Norwegian poet from Ankenes near Narvik , but born in Skjomen .
Giancarlo Bigazzi ( 5 September 1940 -- 19 January 2012 ) was an Italian music producer and composer .
George Cadbury ( 19 September 1839 -- 24 October 1922 ) was the third son of John Cadbury , a Quaker who founded Cadbury 's cocoa and chocolate company .
Abdul Qavi Desnavi ( Urdu : عبدالقوى دسنوى , 1 November 1930 -- 7 July 2011‎ ) was an Indian Urdu language writer , critic , bibliographer , and linguist .
Sir Thomas Cookes , 2nd Baronet ( bap . 1648 -- 8 June 1701 ) , benefactor of Worcester College , Oxford , was the eldest son of Sir William Cookes , 1st Baronet , of Norgrove Court , Worcestershire , and his second wife , Mercy , née Dinely .
Thomas Beccon or Becon ( c. 1511 - -1567 ) was an English cleric and Protestant reformer from Norfolk .
Sir Roger Martin , 1st Baronet ( c. 1639 - 8 July 1712 ) was son of Richard Martin and Jane , daughter of Sir Henry Bedingfield of Oxborough .
Robert McQueen , Lord Braxfield ( 4 May 1722 -- 30 May 1799 ) was a Scottish advocate and judge .
Giovanni Spoldi ( died 1904 ) was an Italian painter , active mainly in the Veneto , painting vedute of marine scenes .
Pietro Cavallini ( 1259 -- c. 1330 ) was an Italian painter and mosaic designer working during the late Middle Ages .
Hsien Wu ( 吳憲 , Simplified Chinese 吴宪 and Hanyu Pinyin Wú Xiàn ; 24 November 1893 - 8 August 1959 ) was a Chinese protein scientist .
Harold Baer Sr . ( 1905 - 1987 ) was a long - serving New York Supreme Court justice .
Commander Frank Gilbert Hackforth - Jones R.N. ( 1900 - -1982 ) was a British author of the mid 20th century .
Sam Brody ( 1907 - 1987 ) was a founding member of the Workers Film and Photo League , an independent organization founded in 1931 to produced and present films documenting the Great Depression from a Marxist perspective .
William Welwod ( 1578 - -1622 ) was a Scottish jurist who was the first to formulate the laws of the sea in an insular Germanic language .
Guido Dessauer ( 7 November 1915 -- 13 January 2012 ) was a German physicist , specialized in paper engineering , a business executive , writer , art collector , patron of arts , and academic .
Charles Gauthier ( 7 December 1831 -- 5 January 1891 ) was a French sculptor who was made a Chevalier of the Légion d'Honneur in 1872 .
Lin Qiaozhi ( Chinese : 林巧稚 ; pinyin : Lín Qiǎozhì ; Dec. 23 , 1901 -- Apr. 22 , 1983 ) was a Chinese physician , born in Gulangyu on December 23 , 1901 .
Heilwige Bloemardinne ( 1265 ? -- 23 August 1335 ) was a Christian mystic who lived in Brussels and was loosely associated with the Brethren of the Free Spirit .
Antoine Bournonville ( 19 May 1760 -- 11 January 1843 ) was a French ballet dancer , actor , singer and a choreographer , active in the Royal Swedish Ballet and the Royal Danish Ballet and eventually ballet master in the latter .
Derry Hayes ( c. 1928 -- March 2005 ) was an Irish sportsperson who played hurling with the Cork senior inter - county team in the 1950s .
Albert Blan ( born 13 January 1930 in Wigan , Lancashire , died 27 September 2015 ) was an English professional rugby league footballer of the 1940s , ' 50s and ' 60s playing at representative level for England , and at club level for Wigan ' A ' and Swinton .
Pope Stephen VI ( Latin : Stephanus VI ; died August 897 ) was Pope from 22 May 896 to his death in 897 .
Saint Begu ( died 31 October 690 ) was a nun and later became a saint from Hackness , Yorkshire ( Deira ) .
Cao Mao ( 241 - -260 ) , courtesy name Yanshi , was the fourth emperor of the state of Cao Wei during the Three Kingdoms period .
Douglas Clyde Macintosh ( 1877 - -1948 ) was a theologian who did his graduate work at the University of Chicago and then joined Yale in 1909 , becoming an assistant professor of systematic theology .
Sir John Charles Fenton ( 5 May 1880 -- 3 January 1951 ) was a Scottish lawyer .
Trajko Prokopiev ( Macedonian : Трајко Прокопиев ; Kumanovo , Ottoman Empire , 6 November 1909 - Belgrade , Yugoslavia , 21 January 1979 ) was a Macedonian composer .
George Henry Stokes ( 22 June 1876 -- 19 April 1959 ) was a National Government and Progressive Conservative party member of the Canadian House of Commons .
John Corvinus ( Hungarian : Corvin János , Croatian : Ivaniš Korvin ; 2 April 1473 -- 12 October 1504 ) King of Bosnia ( 1495 - -1499 ) .
Slobodan Princip ( Serbian Cyrillic : Слободан Принцип ; May 25 , 1914 -- May , 1942 ) , nicknamed Seljo ( Сељо ) , was a Yugoslav Partisan fighter and the district staff chief of Partisan Sarajevo Oblast during World War II . He was posthumously awarded the Hero of Yugoslavia .
Prince Sisowath Ritharavong ( born on February 6 , 1935 -- 1975 ) was the father of Prince Sisowath Sararith , son of Prince Sisowath Sisura ( line of Prince Sisowath Essaravong ) .
Lilly Reich ( 16 June 1885 - -14 December 1947 ) was a German modernist designer .
Ralph Henry Carless Davis ( 7 October 1918 in Oxford -- 12 March 1991 in Oxford ) , always known publicly as R. H. C. Davis , was a British historian and educator specialising in the European Middle Ages .
Nasim Amrohvi or Naseem Amrohvi ( 1908 - -1987 ) Urdu:نسیم امروہوی , was an Urdu poet , philosopher , and lexicographer who was born as Syed Qaim Raza Taqvi on 24 August 1908 in Amroha , India .
Milton Lazarus ( born in 1898 or 1899 - died March 1 , 1955 ) was an American playwright and screenwriter .
Franz Johannsen ( May 4 , 1921 -- 2006 ) was a German sprint canoer who in the 1950s .
Professor James Halloran ( died 16 May 2007 ) was a British communication scholar known for his contribution for the establishment of the field of media studies in the United Kingdom .
Gebhard Moltke ( 20 February 1764 -- 20 December 1851 ) was a Danish nobleman and civil servant .
Sir ( Harry ) Vincent Lloyd - Jones ( 16 October 1901 -- 23 September 1986 ) was a Welsh barrister who later became a judge of the High Court .
Eugenie Duggan ( 1872 -- 2 November 1936 ) was a popular Australian stage actress .
Georg Sigl ( 13 January 1811 , Breitenfurt bei Wien - 9 May 1887 , Vienna ) was an Austrian mechanical engineer and entrepreneur .
Patricia Schartle Myrer ( 1923 - -2010 ) was an editor , literary agent and publishing executive based in New York City .
Isaac Arthur Pereyre ( 1863 - 1934 ) was a Jewish activist in Bayonne ( in Southern France ) , and a commandant in the French army .
Sir Thomas Gascoigne , 8th Baronet ( 7 March 1745 -- 11 February 1810 ) was born in Cambrai , the third son of Sir Edward Gascoigne , 6th Baronet and a member of the Gascoigne family .
Giuseppe Bertoloni ( 16 September 1804 in Sarzana -- 19 December 1874 in Bologna ) was an Italian botanist and entomologist .
William Byron , 4th Baron Byron ( 4 January 1669/70 -- 8 August 1736 ) was Gentleman of the Bedchamber to Prince George of Denmark .
Richard Hayley Lever ( 28 September 1875 -- 6 December 1958 ) was an Australian - American painter , etcher , lecturer and art teacher .
Scrope Berdmore D.D. ( 1708 - -1770 ) was an English clergyman .
Icewind Dale II is a role - playing video game developed by Black Isle Studios and published by Interplay Entertainment , released on August 27 , 2002 .
Might and Magic IX is a role - playing video game , the last developed by New World Computing for Microsoft Windows and released in 2002 by the 3DO Company .
World of Goo is a puzzle video game developed and published by independent game developer 2D Boy .
Track & Field II ( known in Japan as Konamik Sports in Seoul ) is a sequel to Track & Field created by Konami for the NES in 1988 .
The Multidimensional Personality Questionnaire ( MPQ ) is a personality test meant to measure normal personality developed by Auke Tellegen in 1982 .
Death by Degrees is an action - adventure game by Namco .
Amped 3 is a snowboarding game , the third installment of the Amped sports game franchise , developed by Indie Built/2 K Sports and released on November 22 , 2005 .
Super Monaco GP ( スーパーモナコGP ) is a Formula One racing simulation video game released by Sega , originally as a Sega X Board arcade game in 1989 , followed by ports for multiple video game consoles and home computers in the early 1990s .
Killing Floor 2 is a first - person shooter video game developed by Tripwire Interactive .
Dirt Track Racing 2 ( DTR2 ) is a video game by the now defunct Ratbag Games .
Sub - Terrania is a multidirectional shooter developed by Zyrinx and published by Scavenger , Inc ..
Coincident with that , the PhoneGap code was contributed to the Apache Software Foundation to start a new project called Apache Cordova .
Bang Attack is a video game for WiiWare developed by Netherlands - based Engine Software .
Witchaven is a fantasy first - person shooter video game with action role - playing game elements , developed by Capstone Software and published by Intracorp Entertainment in 1995 .
The Adreno series of graphics processing units ( GPUs ) are semiconductor intellectual property cores developed by Qualcomm and used in a variety of their SoCs .
Rampage Puzzle Attack is a puzzle game for Game Boy Advance , developed by Finnish development house Ninai Games and published by Midway Games .
Mobile Forces is a first - person shooter computer game developed by Rage Software and published by Majesco using the first generation of the Unreal Engine .
The Bible Game is a Christian - themed party game developed by Crave Entertainment .
H2Overdrive is a powerboat arcade racing game developed by Specular Interactive and released in 2009 by Raw Thrills .
Wonder World Amusement Park is a video game for seventh generation consoles developed by Coyote Console and published by Majesco Entertainment .
Army Attack is a social networking strategy video game developed by Digital Chocolate .
A-10 Attack ! is a combat flight simulator for the Apple Macintosh computer released by Parsoft Interactive in 1995 .
X - Plane Airliner is a game for the iOS and WebOS developed and published by Laminar Research .
Total Annihilation is a real - time strategy video game created by Cavedog Entertainment , a sub - division of Humongous Entertainment , and released on September 30 , 1997 by GT Interactive for Microsoft Windows and Mac OS . It was the first real - time strategy game to feature 3D units and terrain .
Football Manager is a series of football management simulation games developed by Sports Interactive and published by Sega .
Spyglass Board Games is a video game developed by independent software developers Freeverse Software and Strange Flavour for the Xbox 360 's Xbox Live Arcade service .
Word Rescue is an educational platform game written by Karen Crowther ( Chun ) of Redwood Games and released by Apogee Software in March , 1992 .
Flimbo 's Quest is a 2D platform game published by British publishing house System 3 ( later renamed to Studio 3 Interactive ) for the Commodore 64 , Amiga , Atari ST and Amstrad CPC .
Jump Raven was the second game released by Cyberflix , in 1994 .
Voice Fantasy is a 2010 action game developed and published by Square Enix and released for the Apple iOS platforms .
Game of Thrones Ascent is a strategy video game developed by Disruptor Beam for iPad , Facebook , Kongregate .
Under Defeat is a shoot 'em up arcade game by G.rev .
Amazing Tater ( known in Japan as Puzzle Boy II ( パズルボーイII ) ) is a puzzle video game for the Game Boy from Atlus .
Machines at War is a real - time strategy video game developed by Isotope 244 .
KnightShift , also known as Polanie II and Once Upon a Knight , is a real - time strategy and role - playing video game hybrid developed by Reality Pump Studios and released by Topware Interactive for the PC Windows and OS X in 2003 .
Simon the Sorcerer is an adventure game that was released by Adventure Soft on 2 January 1993 for Amiga and DOS formats .
Heart of China is a 1991 adventure game developed by Dynamix and published by Sierra On - line .
The CMU Pronouncing Dictionary ( also known as CMUdict ) is an open source pronouncing dictionary originally created by the Speech Group at Carnegie Mellon University ( CMU ) for use in speech recognition research .
Winning Post 7 Maximum 2008 ( ウイニングポスト7 マキシマム2008 ) is a multiplatform horse racing simulator published by Koei for the PlayStation 2 , PlayStation 3 , Wii and Microsoft Windows It was released only in Japan on March 13 , 2008 .
Twin Cobra , released in Japan as Kyukyoku Tiger ( 究極タイガー Kyūkyoku Taigā ) , is a 1987 helicopter - themed shoot 'em up arcade game developed by Toaplan .
Jonathan of the Night is a 1987 short horror film written , produced and directed by Buddy Giovinazzo .
Fuori uno sotto un altro ... arriva il passatore ( internationally released as Holy God , Here Comes the Passatore ! , God Help Us , Here Comes the Passatore ! and Holy God , It 's the Passatore ) is a 1973 Italian adventure - comedy film directed by Giuliano Carnimeo .
The Flanagan Boy ( released in the United States as Bad Blonde ) is a 1953 British film noir directed by Reginald Le Borg .
Pyaar Mein Kabhi Kabhi ( English : Sometimes in love ) is a 1999 bollywood , romantic comedy , directed by Raj Kaushal .
A Silent Witness is a 1912 Australian silent film directed by Franklyn Barrett .
The Party Animal is a movie written and directed by David Beaird .

Pilar Brabo Castells ( 28 February 1943 -- 21 May 1993 ) was a Spanish politician from the Spanish Socialist Workers ' Party , previously from the Spanish Communist Party .
Eilidh Whiteford ( born 24 April 1969 ) is the Scottish National Party ( SNP ) Member of Parliament ( MP ) for Banff and Buchan .

Lamport 's bakery algorithm is a computer algorithm devised by computer scientist Leslie Lamport , which is intended to improve the safety in the usage of shared resources among multiple threads by means of mutual exclusion .
The Zamboni pile ( also referred to as a Duluc Dry Pile ) is an early electric battery , invented by Giuseppe Zamboni in 1812 .

Stalinism is the means of governing and related policies implemented by Joseph Stalin .
The Rhein - Wupper - Bahn is a Regionalbahn service in the German state of North Rhine - Westphalia .
The Shewhart Medal , named in honour of Walter A. Shewhart , is awarded annually by the American Society for Quality for ... outstanding technical leadership in the field of modern quality control , especially through the development to its theory , principles , and techniques .
Reaganomics ( /reɪɡəˈnɒmɪks/ ; a portmanteau of Reagan and economics attributed to Paul Harvey ) refers to the economic policies promoted by U.S. President Ronald Reagan during the 1980s .
Spinozism ( also spelled Spinoza - ism or Spinozaism ) is the monist philosophical system of Baruch Spinoza which defines `` God '' as a singular self - subsistent substance , with both matter and thought being attributes of such .

School of Stolyarsky ( for gifted children ) is a music school established in Odessa , Ukraine ( former USSR ) in 1933 by the initiation and vision of the eminent violin pedagogue Pyotr Stolyarsky .
The Hume - Rothery rules , named after William Hume - Rothery , are a set of basic rules that describe the conditions under which an element could dissolve in a metal , forming a solid solution .
The Einstein field equations ( EFE ; also known as `` Einstein 's equations '' ) are the set of 10 equations in Albert Einstein 's general theory of relativity that describes the fundamental interaction of gravitation as a result of spacetime being curved by matter and energy .
The Laurent series was named after and first published by Pierre Alphonse Laurent in 1843 .
Fed Cup is the premier international team competition in women 's tennis , launched in 1963 to celebrate the 50th Anniversary of the International Tennis Federation ( ITF ) .
In atomic physics , Hund 's rules refers to a set of rules that German physicist Friedrich Hund formulated around 1927 , which are used to determine the term symbol that corresponds to the ground state of a multi - electron atom .
The Taxil hoax was an 1890s hoax of exposure by Léo Taxil intended to mock not only Freemasonry but also the Roman Catholic Church 's opposition to it .
In geometry , the Euler line , named after Leonhard Euler ( /ˈɔɪlər/ ) , is a line determined from any triangle that is not equilateral .
USS Grayling ( SSN-646 ) , a Sturgeon - class attack submarine , was the fifth ship of the United States Navy to be named for the grayling .
Ebstein 's anomaly was named after Wilhelm Ebstein , who in 1866 described the heart of the 19-year - old Joseph Prescher .
Hilbert 's eleventh problem is one of David Hilbert 's list of open mathematical problems posed at the Second International Congress of Mathematicians in Paris in 1900 .
The Wittig reaction was discovered in 1954 by Georg Wittig , for which he was awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1979 .
In British politics , the term Blairism refers to the political ideology of former leader of the Labour Party and Prime Minister Tony Blair , who left both positions in 2007 to become Envoy of the Quartet on the Middle East .
The Hubble sequence is a morphological classification scheme for galaxies invented by Edwin Hubble in 1926 .
Rubicline , also referred to as Rb - microcline , is the rubidium analogue of microcline , an important tectosilicate mineral .

Robert Mark Goresky ( born 1950 ) is a Canadian mathematician who invented intersection homology with Robert MacPherson .

Tibor Šalát ( May 13 , 1926 -- May 14 , 2005 ) was a Slovak mathematician , professor of mathematics , and Doctor of Mathematics who specialized in number theory and real analysis .
Val Lewton ( May 7 , 1904 -- March 14 , 1951 ) was a Russian - American film producer and screenwriter best known for a string of low - budget horror films he produced for RKO Pictures in the 1940s .
Yasmine Petty is a transgender American model of Moroccan and Italian descent .
Lacydes of Cyrene ( Greek : Λακύδης ) , Greek philosopher , was head of the Academy at Athens in succession to Arcesilaus from 241 BC . He was forced to resign c. 215 BC due to ill - health , and he died c. 205 BC . Nothing survives of his works .
Washington Irving ( April 3 , 1783 -- November 28 , 1859 ) was an American author , essayist , biographer , historian , and diplomat of the early 19th century .
Jéssica Andrade ( born September 25 , 1991 ) is a Brazilian mixed martial artist who competes in the Ultimate Fighting Championship 's Bantamweight division .
James David Barber ( July 31 , 1930 -- September 12 , 2004 ) was a political scientist whose book The Presidential Character made him famous for his classification of presidents through their worldviews .
Pandit Vijay Raghav Rao ( Vijaya Raghava Rao ) ( November 3 , 1925 - November 30 , 2011 ) was an Indian flutist , composer , choreographer , musicologist , poet and fiction writer .
Bartholomew W. Hogan ( born on January 29 , 1901 in Quincy , Massachusetts ) was a psychiatrist , professor and Naval officer .
Judith Lewis Herman ( born 1942 ) is a psychiatrist , researcher , teacher , and author who has focused on the understanding and treatment of incest and traumatic stress .
Earl J. Silbert ( March 8 , 1936 ) is a prominent American lawyer who served as United States Attorney for the District of Columbia from 1974 to 1979 , and served , along with two other U.S. Attorneys , as the first prosecutor in the infamous Watergate scandal .
Lynne Mapp Drexler ( 1928 - -1999 ) was an American abstract and representational artist , who was a painter and photographer .

Manju Pillai is the grand daughter of Veteran Malayalam actor S. P. Pillai . She did her undergraduate studies from Mar Ivanious College Trivandrum . She was married to Malayalam cine - serial artist Mukundan Menon & was later divorced . Later she married cinematographer Sujith Vasudev on 23 December 2000 .
JS16 , real name Jaakko Salovaara , is a Finnish musician and record producer .
Vladimir J. Konečni ( born October 27 , 1944 ) is an American and Serbian psychologist , aesthetician , poet , dramatist , fiction writer , and art photographer , currently an Emeritus Professor of Psychology at the University of California , San Diego .
Luigi Astolfi ( Italian pronunciation : ( luˈid͡ʒi asˈtɔlfi ) ; 1790s--1860s ) was an Italian dancer , choreographer , and composer .
Isabelle Blanc ( born July 25 , 1975 ) is a French snowboarder and Olympic champion .
